Is the lead Investigator affiliated with the Florey?

Either paid staff or Term Visitor and acting in this capacity for the study

Lead Investigator = Principal Investigator for the overall study or Florey site
Please continue with the survey below.

Registration in the Florey Clinical Studies Registry is not required.

Thank you - no further action is needed.

Does your project involve:

  • human participants,
  • their data,
  • or biospecimens,

and therefore require Human Research Ethics Committee (HREC) approval?

You are conducting a Florey Clinical Study.

You must register your study in the Florey Clinical Studies Registry.
Please continue with the survey below.

You are not conducting a Florey Clinical Study.

Registration in the Florey Clinical Studies Registry is not required.

Thank you - no further action is needed.

Are you assigning human participants to a health-related intervention to evaluate the effect on health outcomes?

Interventions may be (but are not limited to) pharmaceuticals, devices, biological products, standard care procedures or online/in-person health programs.

You are also conducting a Clinical Trial.

Please continue with the survey below.

You are not conducting a Clinical Trial.

Registration with the Florey Clinical Studies Registry is still required.

As your study does not meet the criteria for a formal clinical trial, we will only collect a core set of summary information to ensure governance compliance.
Please continue with the survey below.

Field Label: Is this person administering a medical procedure?

All team members are required to complete ICH-GCP training before beginning work on the study.
This ensures that everyone involved is aware of Good Clinical Practice principles and their responsibilities under the guidelines.

Free internationally recognised training is available here:
https://globalhealthtrainingcentre.tghn.org/ich-good-clinical-practice

To complete the training:

1. Register

2. Go to "eLearning courses" → "short courses" → select ICH Good Clinical Practice E6 (R2)

3. Allow 45-60 minutes to complete the module

4. A certificate is issued once a minimum of 80% is achieved in the final quiz section.


Certification is valid for 3 years from the date of completion.
You can download and print your certificate for your files.
This training is provided courtesy of The Global Health Network.

Name of manufacturer of therapeutic good
Does the manufacturer have a Good Manufacturing Practice (GMP) license or clearance?

Australian-based manufacturers of medicines and biologicals are required to hold a licence to manufacture.

To obtain a licence, a manufacturer must demonstrate compliance with the relevant code of GMP. Overseas manufacturers of medicines supplied to Australia are also required to meet an acceptable standard of GMP.

It is an offence in Australia to manufacture therapeutic goods for human use without a licence or certification unless exempt under the Therapeutic Goods Act 1989.

Further information may be found via this link.
Is the therapeutic good registered with the TGA?
Please upload a copy of the TGA Notification/Acknowledgement

Sponsors must be aware of the requirements to import, export, manufacture and supply 'unapproved' therapeutic goods or devices in Australia.

For clinical trials, the following avenues are available:

Clinical Trial Notification (CTN) scheme: Sponsors must notify the TGA of the intent to use an 'unapproved' therapeutic good prior to use. Notification is submitted online. A fee applies.

Clinical Trial Approval (CTA, formerly CTX) scheme: Sponsors must submit an application to the TGA if intending to use unapproved high-risk or novel treatments such as Class 4 biologicals.

For details, please visit this link.

Section Header: Study Registration
Field Label: Has the study been registered on a Clinical Trial Registry?

The Declaration of Helsinki now explicitly states that every clinical trial must be registered in a publicly accessible database before recruitment of the first subject.

For example, ANZCTR.

It is highly recommended that all research is registered if you are intending to publish in a journal aligned with the International Committee of Medical Journal Editors (ICMJE).
Has the study been registered on another Clinical Trial Registry?
Has the study been registered on another Clinical Trial Registry?

Section Header: Data Safety Monitoring Committee
Field Label: Has an independent Data Safety Monitoring Committee (DSMC/DSMB) been established?

An independent Data and Safety Monitoring Committee (DSMC) is required if the study is intended to provide information about the effectiveness and/or safety of an intervention.

Phase II and III studies require a DSMC, with the exception of low-risk behavioural and nutritional studies - unless the study is particularly large, long-term, or involves vulnerable subjects.

For further information, please visit this link.

Section Header: Conflicts of Interest
Field Label:
Does the team have any conflicts of interest to declare?

Conflicts of interest might be:

  • Actual e.g. the person receives payment from, or owns shares in, a company involved in the study

  • Potential e.g. the person is applying for additional funding from, or may soon take up a role with, a company involved in the study

  • Perceived e.g. the person has a close personal relationship with, or their group receives unrelated funding from, a company involved in the study

As a conflict of interest has been declared, a Conflict of Interest (COI) Disclosure and Management Form
must be completed as part of the registration process.

A template for this form is available using the link below.
Upload your completed and signed Conflict of Interest form here

Is this considered a Suspected Unexpected Serious Adverse Reaction (SUSAR) or a Significant Safety Issue (SSI)?

Key Characteristics of a SUSAR:

    • Serious: The adverse reaction is serious, meaning it could be fatal, life-threatening, require hospitalization, cause persistent disability, or result in a congenital abnormality.
    • Unexpected: The adverse reaction is not consistent with the expected side effects or severity of the drug as described in the product information (e.g., Investigator Brochure).
    • Suspected Causal Relationship: There is a reasonable possibility that the adverse reaction is due to the Investigational Product (IP).

An SSI is: Any new information that materially raises risk to participants or trial integrity. It may or may not involve an adverse event.

Further information on Safety Reporting may be found here.

Choices, Calculations, OR Slider Labels: 1, Want to know more about GCP certification?

Field Label: Is this person administering a medical procedure?

All team members are required to complete ICH-GCP training before beginning work on the study.
This ensures that everyone involved is aware of Good Clinical Practice principles and their responsibilities under the guidelines.

Free internationally recognised training is available here:
https://globalhealthtrainingcentre.tghn.org/ich-good-clinical-practice

To complete the training:

1. Register

2. Go to "eLearning courses" → "short courses" → select ICH Good Clinical Practice E6 (R2)

3. Allow 45-60 minutes to complete the module

4. A certificate is issued once a minimum of 80% is achieved in the final quiz section.


Certification is valid for 3 years from the date of completion.
You can download and print your certificate for your files.
This training is provided courtesy of The Global Health Network.
